Despite giving up direct control to subcontractors and franchises, these large companies have figured out how to maintain the quality of brand-name products and services, without the cost of maintaining an expensive workforce. But from the perspective of workers, this strategy has meant stagnation in wages and benefits and a lower standard of living. Weil proposes ways to modernize regulatory policies so that employers can meet their obligations to workers while allowing companies to keep the beneficial aspects of this business strategy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIndustrial relationszUnited States. 0aLaborzUnited States. 0aManpower planningzUnited States. 0aQuality of work lifezUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067472612340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674726123423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674726123.jpg  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles